The grass-specialist leafhopper tribe
Chiasmini Distant, 1908
( Hemiptera : Cicadellidae : Deltocephalinae ) includes 324 species in 21 genera worldwide. Some of these species are important agricultural pests because of their ability to suck plant sap and spread plant pathogens. Adults and nymphs feed on phloem sap, resulting in inhibition of plant growth and development, yellowing of leaves and withering of the whole plant. Some species of
Nephotettix Matsumura, 1902
transmit rice common dwarf disease, verticillium wilt disease and yellow dwarf disease, which can cause substantial economic and yield losses (
). Species of
Exitianus Ball, 1929
are important vectors of corn stunt (
), Napier grass stunt disease (
), and Bermuda grass white leaf phytoplasma (
).

